lzh_formatted:
  title: 壽藺
  author: 申叔舟
  language: lzh
  text: 天運坱圠無停機。人事變化隨遷移。坐見桑田爲蒼海。隙駟滅沒須臾期。先王乘運撫瑤圖。手整乾坤提綱維。至治馨香徹上帝。奇祥異瑞爭紛披。休聲仁化暢遐邇。梯航萬里來相追。當時藺師亦遠至。風格飄然來雙眉。先王一見授書幣。面命歸報國王知。上人拭目感榮遇。擧手拜命辭丹墀。間關三載今始回。殯宮寂寞垂玄帷。手擎國書復舊命。爐煙一炷悲風吹。人人見師暗悽惻。老臣血淚雙漣洏。念師往復只數載。天崩地拆非所期。師言鯨濤不足畏。滿國白刃交參差。連年鼙鼓尙未已。都中列壘方相持。萬死一生捐性命。出入劒戟如坦夷。天語丁寧猶在耳。敢爲知遇論嶮危。殉義輕身重然諾。慷慨燕趙秋風悲。昔我泛海窮東溟。綵纜手繫扶桑枝。馬島松浦隔海隅。九州山勢西南趍。莒崎斜連覇家臺。白沙十里松萬株。黑水揚波沒涯涘。平生漂梗緣桑弧。赤關尾路兵庫津。淡路四州羅星辰。王都百里山作城。西北嵯峩東嶙峋。三川流惡南注海。町條井井街巷勻。南仙相國領諸寺。觚稜日照輝金銀。似聞干戈起輦轂。朱門寶刹俱灰塵。栖芳有寺在西山。洞府幽深隔人寰。客中暫凭潭北軒。往往魂夢尋淸閑。光陰倏忽三十秋。胸中歷歷懷舊遊。眼底紛紛田與海。天時人事同悠悠。撫今念舊重悲感。扶桑照檻空白頭。
korean:
  title: 일본 중 수인
  author: 신숙주
  language: kor
  text: |-
    하늘의 운행이 광대하여 멈춤이 없고
    인사가 변화하여 수시로 옮기니
    상전이 벽해 됨도 앉아서 볼 수 있고
    틈으로 사마 지나듯 재빠른 세월
    선왕께서 운을 타
    손수 건곤을 정돈하사 기강을 세우시니
    덕의 향기가 상제께 사무쳐
    기이한 상서가 연하여 나타났네
    아름다운 소문 어진 교화가 원근에 퍼지니
    축하의 사절들 만리 밖에서 다투어 왔네
    그때 인사도 먼 곳에서 이르니
    두 눈썹에 나타난 표연한 풍격
    선왕이 인견하시고 국서와 폐백을 주시며
    돌아가 국왕에게 드리라 명하셨네
    스님이 눈을 씻고 영우에 감격되어
    손 들어 명 받잡고 단치에서 물러나온 뒤
    그럭저럭 3년, 이제야 귀국하려는데
    선왕께서 승하하사 빈궁이 적막하시니
    국서를 손에 받들고 구명을 아뢸 제
    향연 심지에 슬픈 바람이 불어
    사람들 스님 보고 모두 슬퍼하였고
    노신은 피눈물이 줄줄이 흘렀네
    생각하니 스님의 왕복이 겨우 몇 해인데
    천붕지탁(천자(天子)가 죽는 것을 말하나다)의 실로 뜻밖의 일
    스님 말이, 바닷물결 무섭지 않사외다
    나라 가득히 칼 놀음이 벌어져
    몇 해째 전쟁이 아직 안 멎은 판국
    왕도에도 성을 쌓고 각기 상지하는 터이니
    만사일생으로 목숨을 내걸고
    창검 사이로 출입함을 큰길같이 하였소
    천어(임금의 말)가 정녕하여 아직도 귀에 쟁쟁
    지우를 입사온 터라 한 몸 위험을 논하리까
    그 의에 죽고 약속을 존중하는 태도
    연ㆍ조다운 강개에 가을 바람도 슬퍼하네
    옛날 내가 바다에 떠 동해 끝까지 갔을 때
    채색 닻줄을 부상 가지에 손수 매니
    대마도 송포가 바다 한 구석에 있고
    구주의 산세는 서남으로 뻗었는데
    거기 비스듬 저쪽이 패가대(일본 박다(博多))
    10리 백사장에 만 그루 소나무
    흑수의 높은 물결 가없이 퍼진 데를
    상호(호시(弧矢)와 같다)의 큰 뜻으로 평지처럼 떠돌았네
    적간관ㆍ미로ㆍ병고 나루
    별처럼 나란한 담로 네 고을
    왕도(일본 경도(京都))는 백 리 넓이, 산으로 성을 삼아
    서북쪽 드높고 동쪽도 삐죽삐죽
    세 내가 남으로 흘러 바다로 드는데
    시가는 정자 모양 쪽쪽 고르네
    남선 상국이 거느린 여러 절
    금각 은각이 해 비쳐 눈부시고
    들으니, 앞서 왕도에 전쟁이 나서
    주문 보찰이 모두 재가 되었다던가
    서산에 있는 서방이란 절
    골안이 깊숙하여 세속을 떠난 곳
    객중에 잠깐 담북헌에 올라서
    이따금 청한한 꿈 꾸었지
    세월이 빨라 어느덧 30년
    가슴속엔 옛 놀이가 아직도 역력하여라
    눈앞의 분분한 일 상전과 벽해
    천시와 인사가 한가지로 유유하네
    지금 생각 옛추억에 거듭 슬퍼하노라니
    부상 해 비친 난간에 내 머리만 희었네
  url: https://db.itkc.or.kr/dir/item?itemId=BT#dir/node?dataId=ITKC_BT_1365A_0110_010_0600&viewSync=OT
  footnotes:
  - key: '[주-D001] 연(燕)ㆍ조(趙) : '
    value: 이 두 지방은 옛날에 협객(俠客)이 많이 났고, 의협적인 강개의 풍이 있었다.
english:
  title: In Praise of Zen Master Suin
  author: Shin Suk-ju
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Heaven's wheel turns vast and boundless, never pausing—
    human affairs transform and shift with each passing season.
    I have watched mulberry fields become azure seas,
    and swift seasons vanish like a horse's shadow through a gap.

    The Former King, riding fortune's tide,
    with his own hand set heaven and earth in order, establishing the vital thread.
    The fragrance of virtue ascended to the Celestial Court,
    and auspicious omens appeared in profusion.

    Fair renown and benevolent teaching spread far and near—
    from ten thousand miles away, envoys rushed to compete in their arrival.
    Then came Master Suin from distant lands,
    his presence ethereal as wind, bearing grace upon his brow.

    The Former King received him and presented scrolls and gifts,
    commanding him to return and inform his sovereign lord.
    The Master wiped his eyes, moved by such honor,
    raised his hands to receive the mandate, and withdrew from the crimson steps.

    Three uncertain years have passed, and now at last he returns—
    yet the royal palace stands empty in mourning's desolate silence.
    Holding the royal missive in trembling hands,
    the temple incense curls while mournful winds sweep through.

    All who see the Master grow sorrowful and still—
    this aged minister's tears flow like twin streams.
    Thinking of his journeys, spanning mere years,
    when heaven collapsed and earth cracked—who could have foreseen?

    Yet the Master spoke: "The whale-tossed waves need not be feared."
    While across the kingdom, blades clashed without ceasing,
    and war-drums rumbled year after year with no end in sight,
    and the capital itself was ringed with fortifications.

    He cast ten thousand lives for one—
    walking through spear and sword as on level ground,
    the royal words still ring clear in his ears:
    can he now speak of danger to one he owes such debt?

    He chose righteousness over his own body, held his promise sacred—
    with the generosity of Yan and Zhao, whose autumn winds turn mournful.

    Once I sailed across the sea to the eastern horizon's rim,
    my silken anchors knotted by hand to the boughs of Fusang.
    Major and Matsura lay separate across the waters,
    while the nine provinces stretched their mountains southwest.

    Gifu leaned diagonally toward the Hakudata coast,
    ten miles of white sand and ten thousand pines—
    the black sea lifted its waves beyond all reckoning,
    and I drifted like duckweed on the archer's arc of fate.

    Akimi, Miroad, and Hyogo strait,
    Awaji and four provinces starred in constellation—
    the royal capital spread a hundred miles wide, mountains forming its walls,
    steep and jagged to the northwest, ridged and sharp to the east.

    Three rivers flowed southward toward the sea,
    the city laid out square and even, streets in perfect order.
    The southern minister held sway over countless temples,
    their golden and silver eaves shimmering in the sun.

    I heard that war had come to the capital itself,
    and the great temples turned to ash and ruin.
    West Mountain held a temple called Seiho,
    its cave sanctuary deep, removed from the world of dust.

    I climbed briefly onto a northern hall by the deep pool,
    and often dreamed of clarity in those quiet hours.
    Thirty autumns have slipped away in haste,
    yet the old journeys remain vivid still within my heart.

    Before my eyes, the fields and seas shift ceaselessly—
    both heaven's time and human affairs flow on alike.
    Recalling now, brooding on what once was,
    my hair has turned white beneath Fusang's distant light.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Yan and Zhao were ancient Chinese regions renowned for their noble, chivalrous spirit and righteous abandon—a fitting comparison to describe Suin's unwavering virtue and loyalty.
  - key: ''
    value: Fusang is a mythical tree symbolizing Japan in classical Chinese poetry, located at the far eastern edge of the world.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Former King' refers to the reigning Korean monarch whom Suin served; the poem was written after this king's death, giving poignancy to Suin's delayed return from Japan.
  - key: ''
    value: Suin was a historical figure who served as a diplomat and Buddhist monk, traveling between Korea and Japan during the 15th century amid times of political upheaval.
